   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Brown_25358_1824-03_page01.jpg"/>
            <opener>
               <dateline> 
                  <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Edgeworthstown_IE">Edgeworthstown</placeName><lb/>
                  <date when="1824-03-04"/>March 4<hi rend="superscript">h</hi>. 1824</dateline><lb/>
            </opener>
            <p>You have obliged me much by the<lb/>
               present you have made me, Sir, of your<lb/>
               travels in Europe - Though they could<lb/>
               not contain so much positive novelty<lb/>
               for us as they do for the Americans<lb/>
               yet they will not be less interesting<lb/>
               to the old than to the new World<lb/></p>
            <p>. The interest of curiosity may not be<lb/>
               so great but that of self love is still<lb/>
               greater. We are anxious to see how<lb/>
               European things and persons strike<lb/>
               Americans - It happens that you<lb/>
               have given accounts of persons and<lb/>
               things in <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#ENK">England</placeName>, <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#STK">Scotland</placeName>, <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#FR">France</placeName><lb/>
               <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Geneva_SZ">Geneva</placeName>, and <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#SZ"><choice><orig>Swisserland</orig><reg>Switzerland</reg></choice></placeName>, which my sisters<lb/>
               <add>&amp; I</add> have recently visited - And many of the<lb/>
               persons whom you mention are our<lb/>
               particular friends. To the justice and<lb/>
               spirit of all the delineations of what<lb/>
               we have seen we can bear full testimony<lb/>
               and from these we are reasonably led to<lb/>
               infer<lb/>
               <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Brown_25358_1824-03_page02.jpg"/>
            that all your representations of what<lb/>
            we have not seen are equally accurate.<lb/></p>
            <p>Your account of the Manufactures<lb/>
               of the <unclear>Hield</unclear> for one instance, gives as<lb/>
               much information as possible in a small<lb/><lb/>
               compass &amp; must therefore be valuable<lb/>
               to foreigners who are <add>most</add> curious to know<lb/>
               how the toys in the great Toy shop of<lb/>
               Europe are produced with such celerity<lb/>
               and perfection - I am sorry you did not see<lb/>
               <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Birmingham_ENK">Birmingham</placeName> - and <persName ref="./Personography.xml#WattJ1"> <hi rend="underline">Watts</hi></persName> |-<lb/>
               Your work has reached me but<lb/> 
               a few days and I have not yet <choice><orig>finish<lb/>
                  ed</orig><reg>finished</reg></choice> reading it; but as I have an <choice><orig>oppor-<lb/>
                     -tunity</orig><reg>opportunity</reg></choice> of <del>writing</del> sending this letter<lb/>
               by a person who is going to <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Philadelphia_PA_US"><choice><orig>Philadel-<lb/>
                  -phia</orig></choice><reg>Philadelphia</reg></placeName> I cannot delay to offer you my<lb/>
               acknowledgements though they must<lb/>
               be insufficient as I have not yet<lb/>
               seen the extent of my obligation<lb/>
               I have seen enough however to<lb/>
               judge of the spirit of candor and <choice><orig>li-<lb/>
                  berality</orig><reg>liberality</reg></choice> and the freedom from <choice><orig>na-<lb/>
                     <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Brown_25358_1824-03_page03.jpg"/>
                     tional</orig><reg>national</reg></choice> jealousy evinced in your work<lb/>
               - I wish that this spirit which does<lb/><lb/>
               so much honor to the character of <del>the</del><lb/>
               <add>each</add> individual &amp; which is the true policy<lb/>
               of every nation, were more general<lb/>
               between <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#US">America</placeName> and <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#ENK">England</placeName>-<lb/>
               It is now becoming <hi rend="underline">fashionable</hi><lb/>
               indeed in <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#London_ENK">London</placeName> to <hi rend="underline">speak</hi> well of<lb/>
               Americans &amp; I hope the fashion of<lb/>
               writing with liberality will follow in<lb/>
               among our best authors &amp; yours.<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#IrviW1">Washington <choice><orig>Irvine</orig><reg>Irving</reg></choice></persName> has set an <choice><orig>ex-<lb/>
                  cellent</orig><reg>excellent</reg></choice> example - In others of your<lb/>
               writers &amp; of panegyrists of their<lb/>
               country I have regretted to observe<lb/>
               the talents they individually possess<lb/>
               and the grand facts they had to <choice><orig>pro-<lb/>
                  duce</orig><reg>produce</reg></choice> in favor of <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#US">America</placeName> marred<lb/>
               and disgraced by this sort of national<lb/>
               spirit of monopoly <del>&amp;<unclear>depreciation</unclear></del><lb/>
               Let them raise &amp; glorify their country<lb/>
               &amp; exult in her talents &amp; triumphs in<lb/>
               arts &amp; sciences as much as they will<lb/>
               <pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_Brown_25358_1824-03_page04.jpg"/>
               in this they may be sure of the concurrence<lb/>
               of the wise and the sympathy of the<lb/>
               good, and the indulgence of all. Even<lb/>
               if they exaggerate a little in favor<lb/>
               of their country it is an amicable <choice><orig>weak-<lb/>
               ness</orig><reg>weakness</reg></choice> for which there should be, &amp; <hi rend="underline">is</hi>, a<lb/>
               <choice><orig>give=and=take=charter</orig><reg>give-and-take charter</reg></choice> granted by <add>the common</add> custom,<lb/>
               more powerful than the <choice><orig>common-<lb/>
                  law</orig><reg>common law</reg></choice> of nations - But the moment<lb/>
               any one nation or one world begins<lb/>
               to depreciate the other, indulgence<lb/>
               &amp; sympathy cease - &amp; the just informer<lb/>
               is that those who attempt to knock<lb/>
               down others that they may raise <choice><orig>them-<lb/>
                  -selves</orig><reg>themselves</reg></choice> upon the fallen bodies are <choice><orig>consci-<lb/>
                     ous</orig><reg>conscious</reg></choice> that they <del>can not <unclear></unclear></del> are inferior<lb/></p>
            <p>May this insidious and degrading<lb/>
               spirit cease on both sides the Atlantic! Let us all<lb/>
               try to raise ourselves without <choice><orig>lower<lb/>
                  -ing</orig><reg>lowering</reg></choice> others! - May public esteem be<lb/>
               the <add>just</add> reward of every writer, who acts<lb/>
               this laudable example &amp; who <choice><orig>pre-<lb/>
                  serves</orig><reg>preserves</reg></choice>, temper &amp; candor even when<lb/>
               goaded by illiberal criticism or<lb/>
               tempted by vulgar example!<lb/></p>
            <closer>
               I am Sir your obliged Serv<hi rend="superscript">t</hi><lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria Edgeworth</persName><lb/>
               <lb/>
            </closer>
         </div>
